The Literary Magic of Harry Potter
Princeton — — This summer, readers around the world held celebrations marking the 20th anniversary of the first book in J.K. Rowling's Harry Potter series — — Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone (renamed Harry Potter and the Sorcerer’s Stone in the United States). They had ample reason to celebrate.
Since the young wizard first appeared on June 26, 1997, this "boy who lived" has become a symbol of "resilience and perseverance."
Over the past 20 years, the Harry Potter series has expanded to include seven novels, translated into over 70 languages, and has collectively sold 450 million copies.
The eight movies based on this book have earned a cumulative 7 billion dollars, while Harry Potter-themed toys and merchandise have generated an additional 7 billion dollars in revenue.
It is hard to imagine for a specific age and those with a literary mindset, which day the global audience was not enchanted by Rowling's works.
Therefore, I am always amazed when I recall my students' poor reaction to the book "Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone" in the fall of 1999, when I included it in the syllabus for my course on popular literature at Princeton University. I have been teaching the "Bestselling Books in America" series course since 1993.
This course examines popular works from the 17th century to the present, inviting students to reflect on why and in what ways these bestsellers have appealed to their audiences.
At the end of each term, I ask students to choose a final book that represents the popular taste.
In 1999, they chose the first Harry Potter novel.
That year, the波特热 violently attacked the American coast.
In June, the American publisher of this series urgently released the hardcover edition of the second book in the Harry Potter series, "Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets," into bookstores.
The organization also published the third book in the series, "Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban," and the paperback edition of "Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone" on September 8th.
By the end of that month, Rowling's novels had claimed the top three spots on the New York Times Best Seller list, and the paperback edition of "Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone" topped the paperback bestseller chart.
Time magazine even put this glasses-wearing wizard on its cover.
The image of Harry Potter is everywhere in sight.
My students are eager to know why this frenzy is happening.
Oh no, they are completely disappointed.
In their eyes, the Harry Potter series is nothing more than second-rate nonsense, far from matching the cherished series they remember from childhood, such as The Chronicles of Narnia or The Lord of the Rings.
Although their childhood has only just passed a few years ago, they criticize Harry Potter just like many notorious adult critics: "fabricated," "poor writing," "clichéd," and "boring."

In their eyes, Harry had neither miracles, nor wit, nor warmth.
The students' aversion surprised me, but looking back, it was not really anything to be surprised about.
Although adults have always made up a significant part of the audience for Harry Potter, these students were precisely at the wrong age to objectively understand the phenomenon of Harry Potter.
They had already passed the age of accepting new children's books, yet they were too young still to have their own children (I had just had my own child at the time), and they eagerly insisted that although the Harry Potter series was now very popular, it would soon be forgotten.
Second year's autumn, that is, 2000, the next batch of students also chose Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone as the final analysis text, just like their predecessors, confidently rejecting the book.
Let's fast forward to spring 2007.
After putting the course on hold for several years, I taught "Popular American Books" again.
When students chose the final analysis text, they chose Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone.
And I was ready to face their criticism.
But this time, their comments were very positive.
This is a new generation of students, born between 1986 and 1989, who were not university students when they first read Rowling's works, but rather teenagers in their teens, just beginning to enter adolescence. This means they grew up into young adults alongside Harry, Ron, and Hermione.
The same thing happened again in the autumn of 2010.
For these students, "We grew up with Harry Potter" has become a motto, not just a label.
Will Harry fade from memory?
As long as we are still alive, it's impossible.
Since 2010, I have taught a popular books course twice, and in both cases, students chose non-Harry Potter novels for their final reviews.
Are you tired of Potter?
Based on the reviews students gave for Harry Potter in my other course, "Children's Literature," where I taught Rowling's works, this seems unlikely.
Now, I have chosen to include a Harry Potter novel in the syllabus, but I did not choose "Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone," but instead "Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban" — this is my favorite of the seven Harry Potter novels, marking the transition from children's literature to young adult fiction. The book offers complex portrayals of loyalty, betrayal, anger, and compassion.
Many of my students also love this book the most.
But how long will the popularity of the Harry Potter series last?
Every time I teach children's literature, I start with a survey: "Which books in the list did you read as a child?"
In 2010, 86% of people had read Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban.
In 2012, this number rose to 94%.
But in the years that followed, the percentage continued to decline — in 2014 it was 87%, and by 2016 it had dropped to 81%.
These are not scientific, I know.
But I'm curious: next spring, when I teach "Children's Literature" again, will the percentage of students who have read Harry Potter drop below 80%?
Will the facts prove that the students from 1999 to 2000 were right, that Harry Potter's status is continuously declining and will never become an eternal classic?
Or is there a balance point ahead, where the percentage can remain stable and stop declining?
Perhaps Harry's 40th anniversary will tell us the answer.
Until then, I'm happy to invite him into my classroom.
